Got it — you want the **step-by-step process to configure the Docker registry once in the OpenShift cluster pull-secret**, so all MicroStrategy environments (`env01`, `env02`, etc.) can pull images without creating namespace secrets. 👍
This is indeed the **enterprise best practice**.

Below are the **exact steps**.

---

# Step 1 — Check the Current Cluster Pull Secret

The global pull secret is stored in:

```
openshift-config/pull-secret
```

Run:

```bash
oc get secret pull-secret -n openshift-config -o jsonpath='{.data.\.dockerconfigjson}' | base64 -d
```

You will see something like:

```json
{
  "auths": {
    "registry.redhat.io": {},
    "quay.io": {}
  }
}
```

---

# Step 2 — Extract the Pull Secret

Export the current secret:

```bash
oc extract secret/pull-secret -n openshift-config --to=.
```

This will create a file:

```
.dockerconfigjson
```

---

# Step 3 — Generate Authentication String

Create the auth string for your registry:

```bash
echo -n "username:password" | base64
```

Example output:

```
c3ZjLW1zdHI6cGFzc3dvcmQ=
```

---

# Step 4 — Edit the Pull Secret

Open the file:

```bash
vi .dockerconfigjson
```

Add your MicroStrategy registry under `auths`.

Example:

```json
{
  "auths": {
    "registry.redhat.io": {},
    "quay.io": {},
    "docker.artifactrepository.example.com": {
      "auth": "c3ZjLW1zdHI6cGFzc3dvcmQ=",
      "email": "admin@example.com"
    }
  }
}
```

Save the file.

---

# Step 5 — Update the Cluster Pull Secret

Apply the updated file back to OpenShift:

```bash
oc set data secret/pull-secret \
-n openshift-config \
--from-file=.dockerconfigjson=.dockerconfigjson
```

---

# Step 6 — Wait for Machine Config Update

Updating the pull secret triggers a **node configuration update**.

Check status:

```bash
oc get mcp
```

Wait until you see:

```
worker Updated=True
```

---

# Step 7 — Verify Image Pull

Test by pulling an image from your registry:

```bash
oc run test-pod \
--image=docker.artifactrepository.example.com/strsandbox2510/iserver:m2510 \
--restart=Never
```

Check:

```bash
oc get pods
```

If the pod starts successfully, the registry authentication works.

---

# Step 8 — Verify in MicroStrategy Namespace

Create a new namespace:

```bash
oc new-project mstr-env-test
```

Deploy a test pod using your registry image.

If it pulls successfully, your cluster configuration is correct.

---

# Final Result

After this setup:

```
Cluster Pull Secret
        ↓
All Namespaces
        ↓
Pods can pull private registry images
```

You **no longer need to create**:

```
docker-registry-secret
oc secrets link
imagePullSecrets
```

in every environment namespace.

Your MicroStrategy environments (`env01`, `env02`, etc.) will automatically pull images.

---

# Enterprise Architecture (Recommended)

```
Private Registry
       ↓
OpenShift Global Pull Secret
       ↓
MSTR Operator
       ↓
MSTR Environments
```

This is the **standard approach used in enterprise OpenShift platforms**.

